2.2. Generalizations

There are a vast array of models one can construct in this way. For example, there are a set of models with gauge group SU (n) \Theta U (1) (n even). Start with the theory with gauge group SU (n + 1), an antisymmetric tensor and n \Gamma 3 antifundamentals. Throw out those generators of SU (n + 1) which do not lie in an SU (n) \Theta U (1) subgroup, where the U (1) generator is

~T = diag(1; 1; : : : ; 1; \Gamma n): (2:10)

The original chiral fields decompose as

A2 + F1\Gamma n + (n \Gamma 3) \Theta _F\Gamma 1 + (n \Gamma 3) \Theta Sn: (2:11) Here A is an antisymmetric tensor, F ( _F ) is the (anti)fundamental and S a singlet of the SU (n). At the classical level, one can add to this model a superpotential,

W = flabA _F a _F b + *abF _F aSb: (2:12) It is not hard to check that for general matrices fl and *, there are no flat directions; on the other hand, there is a non-anomalous R symmetry, and supersymmetry is broken. To see that there are no flat directions, let us simplify things a bit by taking *ab diagonal.

